definition.value: The E (trans) stereoisomer of 4-hydroxynon-2-enal; it is the primary alpha,beta-unsaturated hydroxyalkenal produced by lipid peroxidation in cells.
An aminopyrimidine, the structure of which is that of trimethoprim (pyrimidine 2,4-diamine and 1,2,3-trimethoxybenzene moieties linked by a methylene bridge) carrying a 6-hydroxy substituent.
The enal that is (E)-non-2-enal substituted with an oxo group at C-4.
An L-histidine derivative that is an adduct formed between the histidine molecule and (2E,4R)-4-hydroxynon-2-enal.
A penicillin in which the substituent at position 6 of the penam ring is a (2R)-2-amino-2-(cyclohexa-1,4-dien-1-yl)acetamido group.
Azobenzene carrying a single sulfonate substituent at the para-position.
A benzenesulfonate that is the conjugate base of p-azobenzenesulfonic acid.
An acyl group formed from nucleophilic cleavage of the beta-lactam ring of azidocillin.
The conjugate acid of piperidine; major species at pH 7.3.
A tripeptide consisting of AcTyrGlyGly with a phenyldiazenyl substituent at the 3-position on the tyrosine phenyl ring.
A tripeptide consisting of AcTyrGlyGly with a (p-carboxyphenyl)diazenyl substituent at the 3-position on the tyrosine phenyl ring.
A tripeptide consisting of betaAlaGlyGly with a 2,4,6-trinitrophenyl) substituent on the nitrogen of beta-alanine.
A tripeptide consisting of betaAlaGlyGly with a 4-hydroxy-3-iodo-5-nitrophenylacetyl substituent on the beta-alanine nitrogen.
An acyl group formed from nucleophilic cleavage of the beta-lactam ring of phenethicillin
A tripeptide consisting of AcTyrGlyGly with a (4-trimethylammoniophenyl)diazenyl group at the 3-position on the tyrosine phenyl ring.
An  aminonaphthalenesulfonic acid fluorophore with a structure consisting of ethylenediamine substituted on the nitrogens with iodoacetyl and 5-sulfonyl-1-naphthyl groups.
A butan-4-olide having a methylidene group at the 3-position and a 9-(2,3-dihydroxyphenyl)nonyl substituent at the 5-position.
An azide carrying a (4-hydroxy-3-nitrophenyl)acetyl substituent.
The citrate salt of sildenafil.
A univalent carboacyl group formed by loss of OH from the carboxy group of 6-[(4-hydroxy-3-nitrophenyl)acetamido]caproic acid.
The conjugate base of 3,4,5-trimethoxybenzoic acid.
A substituent group formed from the amide of 2-(p-hydroxyphenyl)glycine. It constitutes the side chain of amoxicillin (but without specification of stereochemistry).
The amino acid amide that is the amide of 2-(p-hydroxyphenyl)glycine.
A monocarboxylic acid consisting of valeric acid having a 2,3-dimethoxy-4-methylphenyl group attached to C-5.
A  monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 5-(2,3-dimethoxy-4-methylphenyl)pentanoic acid, formed by proton loss from the carboxy group.
The monohydrate of (+)-catechin.
A 1,3-oxazole compound having a beta-styryl substituent at the 2-position, an ethoxymethylene group at the 4-position, and an oxo group at the 5-position.
The (E)-isomer of azobenzene.
The (Z)-isomer of azobenzene.
A carbapenemcarboxylic acid having a 2-(acetamidovinyl)sulfanyl group at the 2-position and an (S)-1-hydroxyethyl group at the 6-position.
An organobromine compound that is bromobenzene substituted at C-2 and -4 with nitro groups.
Iodobenzene substituted at C-2 and -4 with nitro groups.
The diepoxide of 4-vinylcyclohexene.
Conjugate base of N-arachidonoylglycine.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of alpha-sulfophenylacetic acid.
A penicillanic acid having a (6R)-formamido substituent.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 6-formamidopenicillanic acid, formed by proton loss from the carboxy group.
A multi-substituted pyrazolecarboxamide used in the industrial synthesis of sildenafil.
A 4-ethoxy-3-carboxybenzenesulfonamide in which the sulfonamide nitrogen is a member of a piperazine ring.
An organoammonium salt that is the ethanolamine salt of piroctone.
A cyclic hydroxamic acid that consists of 1-hydroxypyridin-2-one bearing methyl and 2,4,4-trimethylpentyl substtituents at positions 4 and 6 respectively.
A drug or agent applied to the skin to control seborrhea or seborrheic dermatitis.
An aliphatic aldoxime resulting from the formal condensation of the carbonyl group of n-butanal with hydroxylamine.
A pyruvic acid having a 1H-imidazol-4-yl substituent at the 3-position.
A  monocarboxylic acid amide, being a derivative of (3,5-dioxopyrazolidin-4-yl)acetamide substituted at nitrogen by a 5-carboxypentyl chain.
A flavanone 7-O-beta-D-glucoside having hesperetin as the flavanone component.
A flavanone glycoside that is hesperitin  having an 2-O-(alpha-L-rhamnopyranosyl)-beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety attached to the 7-hydroxy group.

A  dicarboxylic acid diamide that is a derivative of butyl(hydroxy)malonic acid in which one carboxy group has formed a hydrazide with 1,2-diphenylhydrazine and the other an amide with 6-aminohexanoic acid.
